Gender Distribution: The applicant pool exhibits a gender imbalance, which may suggest different borrowing behaviors or financial engagement levels between genders.

Car Ownership: A significant portion of applicants own cars, suggesting a level of financial stability or lifestyle that involves asset accumulation.

Real Estate Ownership: Over half of the applicants own real estate, indicating a probable factor in their creditworthiness due to asset security.

Income Types: A large majority of applicants are employed, with smaller proportions being pensioners or associated with commercial entities. This points to the working population being the primary applicant segment for credit.

Educational Background: The majority of the applicants have completed secondary education or higher, suggesting a correlation between education levels and the likelihood of seeking credit.

Marital Status: Most applicants are married, which could potentially influence their financial liabilities and credit needs.

Housing Type: The vast majority live in a house/apartment, suggesting a stable living situation, which could be favorable for credit approval.

Occupation Type: Laborers and core staff form the largest occupational groups among applicants, potentially reflecting the socioeconomic status of the majority of applicants.

# Take the log of AMT_INCOME_TOTAL
application_record_df['Log_AMT_INCOME_TOTAL'] = np.log(application_record_df['AMT_INCOME_TOTAL'])
# Take the log of DAYS_BIRTH as age (counted by day frequency)
application_record_df['Log_DAYS_BIRTH'] = np.log(np.abs(application_record_df['DAYS_BIRTH']))

# Convert positive values to 0 for DAYS_EMPLOYED
# Data dictionary explanation: Count backwards from current day(0). If positive, it means the person currently unemployed.
application_record_df['DAYS_EMPLOYED'] = application_record_df['DAYS_EMPLOYED'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x > 0 else x)

# Apply log transformation only to non-zero values of DAYS_EMPLOYED, else set to 0
application_record_df['Log_DAYS_EMPLOYED'] = application_record_df['DAYS_EMPLOYED'].apply(lambda x: np.log(-x) if x < 0 else 0)

# Variables to plot
log_variables = ['Log_AMT_INCOME_TOTAL', 'Log_DAYS_BIRTH', 'Log_DAYS_EMPLOYED']

# Set up the matplotlib figure
fig, axes = plt.subplots(len(log_variables), 1, figsize=(10, 5*len(log_variables)))

# Loop through each variable to draw a histogram
for i, var in enumerate(log_variables):
    # Get the data of the variable
    data = application_record_df[var]
    # Plot histogram
    data.hist(bins=25, ax=axes[i], density=True, alpha=0.6, color='g')
    # Calculate normal distribution parameters
    mu, std = norm.fit(data)

    # Draw a normal distribution fitting line
    xmin, xmax = axes[i].get_xlim()
    x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 100)
    p = norm.pdf(x, mu, std)
    axes[i].plot(x, p, 'k', linewidth=2)

    # Set the title and label
    title = f'Histogram of {var} with Normal Distribution Fit'
    axes[i].set_title(title)
    axes[i].set_xlabel(var)
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Density')

    # Mark mu and std in the upper left corner of the chart
    textstr = f'$\mu={mu:.2f},\ \sigma={std:.2f}$'
    axes[i].text(0.05, 0.95, textstr, transform=axes[i].transAxes, verticalalignment='top')

for ax in axes:
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Computes the cumulative percentage of bad customers based on different past due periods
def calculate_observe(credit, command):
    '''Calculate Observe Window'''

    id_sum = len(set(credit_record_df['ID']))
    credit_record_df['TEMP_STATUS'] = 0

    exec(command)

    minagg = credit_record_df[credit_record_df['TEMP_STATUS'] == 1].groupby('ID')['MONTHS_ON_BOOK'].min()
    minagg = pd.DataFrame(minagg)
    minagg['ID'] = minagg.index
    result_df = pd.DataFrame({'MONTHS_ON_BOOK':range(0,credit_record_df['WINDOW'].max()), 'rate': None})
    due_list = []
    for i in range(0,61):
        due = minagg[minagg['MONTHS_ON_BOOK']  == i]['ID']
        due_list.extend(due)
        result_df.loc[result_df['MONTHS_ON_BOOK'] == i, 'rate'] = len(set(due_list)) / id_sum
    return result_df['rate']

commands = [
    "credit_record_df.loc[credit_record_df['STATUS'].isin(['1', '2', '3', '4', '5']), 'TEMP_STATUS'] = 1",
    "credit_record_df.loc[credit_record_df['STATUS'].isin(['2', '3', '4', '5']), 'TEMP_STATUS'] = 1",
    "credit_record_df.loc[credit_record_df['STATUS'].isin(['3', '4', '5']), 'TEMP_STATUS'] = 1",
    "credit_record_df.loc[credit_record_df['STATUS'].isin(['4', '5']), 'TEMP_STATUS'] = 1",
    "credit_record_df.loc[credit_record_df['STATUS'] == '5', 'TEMP_STATUS'] = 1"
]

over30Days = calculate_observe(credit_record_df, commands[0])
over60Days = calculate_observe(credit_record_df, commands[1])
over90Days = calculate_observe(credit_record_df, commands[2])
over120Days = calculate_observe(credit_record_df, commands[3])
over150Days = calculate_observe(credit_record_df, commands[4])

# Plot the cumulative % of bad customers
window_list = pd.DataFrame({'Past Due > 30 days': over30Days,
                       'Past Due > 60 days': over60Days,
                       'Past Due > days': over90Days,
                       'Past Due > 120 days': over120Days,
                       'Past Due > 150 days': over150Days
                        })

window_list.plot(grid = True, title = 'Cumulative % of Bad Customers Analysis')
plt.xlabel('Months on Books')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative %')
plt.show()

# Drop 'TEMP_STATUS' column
credit_record_df.drop(columns=['TEMP_STATUS'], inplace=True)

  • Low Percentage of Bad Debt: The purple line is close to the bottom of the graph, which indicates that the percentage of loans categorized as bad debt (>150 days past due) is very low relative to the total loan portfolio.

  • Stable After Initial Period: There is an initial rise in the cumulative percentage as the months on books increase, but the line appears to flatten out after about 15 months. This suggests that most of the loans that become bad debt do so relatively around this period, and after a certain point, the likelihood of loans becoming bad debt stabilizes and doesn't increase much.

  • Comparative Performance: Compared to loans that are past due more than 30, 60, 90, and 120 days, the loans that are past due more than 150 days represent a much smaller fraction. This indicates that while there are loans that are late, most of them do not reach the threshold of >150 days past due, which would categorize them as bad debt.

  • To conclude: A 20-months observe window could cover most bad customers. So, this will the observation window for the analysis.

3. Handling Sample Imbalance Using ①SMOTE, ②ADASYN, and ③Borderline-SMOTE¶

In [ ]:
X = merged_df.drop(columns=['Status', 'ClientID', 'Mobile Phone', 'Work Phone', 'Phone', 'Email'])  # Features
y = merged_df['Status']  # Target variable

# Perform one-hot encoding for categorical features
categorical_vars = ['Gender', 'Car', 'Property', 'Income Category', 'Education Level', 'Marital Status', 'Housing Type', 'Occupation']
transformer = ColumnTransformer(transformers=[('encoder', OneHotEncoder(), categorical_vars)], remainder='passthrough')
X_encoded = transformer.fit_transform(X)

# Get the feature names after one-hot encoding
feature_names_encoded = transformer.get_feature_names_out(input_features=X.columns)

# Split the data into training and testing sets (70-30%)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_encoded, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=69)

## Compute confusion_matrix,  False Positives(FP),  False Negatives(FN), False Positive Rate(FPR), False Negative Rate(FNR) ##

# Compute confusion matrix
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_rf_smote)
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(conf_matrix)

# Calculate the False Positive Rate and False Negative Rate
# Since the positive label is 0 (bad debt, what we care about), the layout of the confusion matrix is slightly different
# Note: It is assumed that the positive class label is 0 (bad debt) and the negative class label is 1 (good debt)
# We hope to decrease FP (FPR), since it means we predict some applicant 1 (good debt) when actually he/she will be 0 (bad debt)
TP, FN, FP, TN = conf_matrix.ravel()

# False Positive Rate (FPR) = FP / (FP + TN)
FPR = FP / (FP + TN)

# False Negative Rate (FNR) = FN / (FN + TP)
FNR = FN / (FN + TP)

print(f"False Positive Rate: {FPR}")
print(f"False Negative Rate: {FNR}")

 [   103 127290]]

  • But struggled with class 0, misclassifying 94 cases as class 0 when they were actually class 1, and misclassifying 103 cases as class 1 when they were actually class 0.
  • The false positive rate (FPR) is very low at approximately 0.0008. This indicates a good ability to avoid misclassifying class 1 instances as class 0.
  • The false negative rate (FNR) is much higher at approximately 0.32. This indicates that there is a significant number of class 0 instances that are being misclassified as class 1.

Random Forest with SMOTE:

  • Achieved perfect precision, recall, and F1-score for class 1 (good debts).
  • Struggled with precision, recall, and F1-score for class 0 (bad debts), indicating potential issues with handling the minority class.
  • Moderate AUC-PR for class 0 (0.73) and perfect AUC-PR for class 1.
  • High false negative rate (0.32) indicates significant misclassification of class 0 instances.

XGBoost with SMOTE:

  • Achieved perfect precision, recall, and F1-score for class 1 (good debts).
  • Similar to Random Forest, struggled with precision, recall, and F1-score for class 0 (bad debts).
  • Moderate AUC-PR for class 0 (0.78) and perfect AUC-PR for class 1.
  • Relatively lower false negative rate (0.11) compared to Random Forest.

LightGBM with SMOTE:

  • Achieved perfect precision, recall, and F1-score for class 1 (good debts).
  • Improved precision, recall, and F1-score for class 0 (bad debts) compared to Random Forest and XGBoost.
  • Moderate AUC-PR for class 0 (0.76) and perfect AUC-PR for class 1.
  • Reduced false negative rate (0.16) compared to Random Forest but still higher than XGBoost.

Overall, SMOTE improved the performance of all three models in terms of identifying class 1 instances (good debts), leading to perfect precision, recall, and F1-score. However, SMOTE had varying impacts on the models' ability to handle the minority class (bad debts), with LightGBM showing the most improvement in precision, recall, and F1-score for this class compared to Random Forest and XGBoost. When considering both False Negative Rate (FNR) and False Positive Rate (FPR), XGBoost may be considered better than the other models in this context.

# Calculate the False Positive Rate and False Negative Rate
# Since the positive label is 0 (bad debt, what we care about), the layout of the confusion matrix is slightly different
# Note: It is assumed that the positive class label is 0 (bad debt) and the negative class label is 1 (good debt)
# We hope to decrease FP (FPR), since it means we predict some applicant 1 (good debt) when actually he/she will be 0 (bad debt)
TP, FN, FP, TN = conf_matrix.ravel()

# False Positive Rate (FPR) = FP / (FP + TN)
FPR = FP / (FP + TN)

# False Negative Rate (FNR) = FN / (FN + TP)
FNR = FN / (FN + TP)

print(f"False Positive Rate: {FPR}")
print(f"False Negative Rate: {FNR}")

Overall, all three models trained on the ADASYN-balanced dataset demonstrate high accuracy and perfect precision, recall, and F1-scores for the majority class (class 1 - good debts). However, they exhibit varying performance in identifying the minority class (class 0 - bad debts), with Random Forest achieving the highest recall, followed by LightGBM and then XGBoost. The false positive rate (FPR) and false negative rate (FNR) also vary among the models, with XGBoost having the lowest FPR and LightGBM having the lowest FNR for class 0. Further tuning or exploration is needed to improve the model performances on class 0.

## Precision-Recall Curve ##

# Compute probabilities for each class
y_probs = xgb_model_bsmote.predict_proba(X_test)

recall = dict()
auc_pr = dict()  # Dictionary to store AUC-PR values

    precision[i], recall[i], _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test == i, y_probs[:, i])
    auc_pr[i] = auc(recall[i], precision[i])  # Compute AUC-PR for each class

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

In [ ]:
## Compute confusion_matrix,  False Positives(FP),  False Negatives(FN), False Positive Rate(FPR), False Negative Rate(FNR) ##
# So we want to control **FP**, which means predict some applicant to be 1 (good debt) when actually he/she is in 0 (bad debt))

# Compute confusion matrix
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_xgb_bsmote)
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(conf_matrix)

# Calculate the False Positive Rate and False Negative Rate
# Since the positive label is 0 (bad debt, what we care about), the layout of the confusion matrix is slightly different
# Note: It is assumed that the positive class label is 0 (bad debt) and the negative class label is 1 (good debt)
# We hope to decrease FP (FPR), since it means we predict some applicant 1 (good debt) when actually he/she will be 0 (bad debt)
TP, FN, FP, TN = conf_matrix.ravel()

# False Positive Rate (FPR) = FP / (FP + TN)
FPR = FP / (FP + TN)

# False Negative Rate (FNR) = FN / (FN + TP)
FNR = FN / (FN + TP)

print(f"False Positive Rate: {FPR}")
print(f"False Negative Rate: {FNR}")

Confusion Matrix:
[[   256     35]
 [   236 127157]]
False Positive Rate: 0.001852535068645844
False Negative Rate: 0.12027491408934708
  • The confusion matrix shows that the model has correctly classified the majority of class 1 instances (127157 out of 127393).
  • But struggled with class 0, misclassifying 35 instances as class 0 when they were actually class 1, and misclassifying 236 instances as class 1 when they were actually class 0.
  • The false positive rate (FPR) is relatively low at approximately 0.0019. This indicates a good ability to avoid misclassifying class 1 instances as class 0.
  • The false negative rate (FNR) is moderate at approximately 0.12. This implies that there is a notable number of class 0 instances that are being misclassified as class 1.
